Florian Haas asks on Twitter :
&ldquo;How do you solve reliable rollback. The definition of a reliable rollback being: &lsquo;get reset &ndash;hard &rsquo;, &lsquo;git push -f&rsquo; and then magic happening that returns your infra to the exact state it was at .&rdquo;
The problem is relatively easy to solve with modern infrastructure-as-code for anything that is stateless. It becomes a bit more involved when you are dealing with things with state, such as database instances or Zookeepers or similar things.

Seriously, HR people ask the weirdest questions.    &ldquo;Where do you see yourself in five years?&rdquo;
 For a Twentysomething with no owned property and no family the truthful answer is of course &ldquo;In a different company, twice removed. Not because you suck more than anywhere else, but, like, statistically.&rdquo;
 &ldquo;Where do you see yourself in five years?&rdquo; &ldquo;Week 27 or 28?&rdquo; &ndash; LionKingLee That time when you finish school and university and before you settle down with dependencies that make you immobile - it is an important time in your life.
